    <fluff>
        <overview>The much-delayed Alpha Wolf might have entered production years earlier if not for the overwhelming focus on quickly building up the Wolf Touman. This pushed final development on what should have been the Clan’s third totemic ’Mech back to the start of 3150 In the meantime, the Wolves jump-started production of the totemic Stormwolf with our aid, while full production of the Alpha Wolf only began in the last few months. The flip side of this delay was that the Empire’s scientists reacted to recent developments of their rivals—such as the Jade Phoenix—and when the Alpha Wolf stepped off the lines, the Wolves had truly saved the best for last.</overview>
        <capabilities>The Alpha Wolf’s initial specification called for a blend of the Warwolf and Timber Wolf in an assault ’Mech package, with the Wulfen’s stealth armor. It shares electronics packages with the Wulfen and Warwolf—amongst others—more as a means to streamline development than for any advanced abilities of the systems themselves. Applying the Wulfen’s stealth armor onto an assault ’Mech raised eyebrows initially, although this decision hinged not on a desire for the Alpha Wolf to fill roles traditionally associated with stealth, such as scouting and infiltration. Rather, the benefits that stealth armor offered in disrupting enemy targeting systems cemented the selection, as it would allow the Alpha Wolf to survive longer in standup fights.</capabilities>
        <battlehistory>A pre-production run of the Alpha Wolf was quickly dispersed among front-line Clusters for field testing. In a possible show of strength to prove the Wolf Empire’s potential independence from our services, the Wolves have been most forthcoming with the results of those tests.:br::br::tab:The new OmniMech underwent its trial by fire in the recent battle for Skye, in which two new prototypes were assigned to the Ninth Wolf Guard Striker Cluster to test the A configuration. Shortly before the end of that battle, the Nineteenth Wolf Strikers defended against the Turkina Keshik, while the Ninth caught the Falcons in a pincer from the rear. There was a chance that the Falcons might withdraw and consolidate, putting the Wolves on a single front. The Alpha Wolfs engaged their superchargers and left their Trinary behind. They kept pace with lighter cavalry ’Mechs to hold the Falcons in place. The heavy firepower of the Alpha Wolfs slowed repositioning Falcon Stars, while the faster Wolf ’Mechs cut them off completely. Desperation gave the Falcons strength and fury. More than two Stars of the Ninth fell, but the Alpha Wolfs’ stealth armor performed admirably. They survived the brutal fighting intact and operational. Then they came face to face with a Jade Phoenix and a Shrike. The stealth armor again threw off Falcon aim, rendering futile the limited opportunity fire as their birdlike ’Mechs swooped around the Wolves. The Alpha Wolfs’ pulse laser arsenal, on the other hand, negated the Falcons’ erratic movements as the distance closed. No Falcon walked away from that particular battlefield, and saKhan Ryan Pryde came to realize that neither old nor new Falcon wonder-weapons were infallible.:br::br::tab:The Republic’s counterattack into Wolf Empire space in March 3150 forced Khan Ward to halt his push deeper into the Republic or else face severe disruption to his logistical chain. On Gacrux, three additional Alpha Wolf prototypes assigned to the 271st Wolf Guard Assault Cluster eviscerated the defending Twelfth Triarii Protectors at range. Following the Twelfth’s rout after the death of their commander, the Alpha Wolfs’ firepower and speed were pivotal in hunting down and utterly destroying the Republic troops.</battlehistory>
        <deployment></deployment>
        <variants></variants>
        <notables>Star Captain Mark Bailey: Mark Bailey was captured by the Steel Wolves on Skye in 3134, during Clan Jade Falcon’s first attempt to seize the world. The proud Falcon warrior chafed under the un-Clanlike command style of Anastasia Kerensky. His short time with the Steel Wolves ended when Kerensky turned the unit into a mercenary command. He attempted to return to Jade Falcon territory, but the Wolves captured him and made him a bondsman for the second time in just over a year. He distinguished himself during the formation of the Wolf Empire, and through this circuitous path, he wound up back on Skye in 3150, fighting against the Clan that bred him. His Timber Wolf was lost in the brutal battle, and Khan Ward rewarded his excellent performance with a brand new Alpha Wolf.:br:Star Commander Patrick: Patrick joined Clan Wolf as a bondsman. The Wolf Empire claimed Patrick “Barnacle” Barnes as isorla after crushing a raid by elements of his Silver Hawks Irregulars company. The destruction of his Wraith left him with a prominent scar on his left cheek, which radiates red when he is angered. The Empire’s martial society gave him a purpose he never realized he had been lacking while serving the Marik-Stewart Commonwealth. His complete fixation on improving his skills and demonstrating his expertise in combat earned his place in Gamma Galaxy’s 271st Wolf Guard Assault Cluster. He helped redeem his Cluster’s honor by crushing the Twelfth Triarii Protectors on Gacrux, rising to Star Commander after recording four kills against the Republic unit.</notables>
